hands_on_practices.solution:
We apply the Orbit–Stabilizer Theorem to the conjugation action of $S_7$.  
1. The size of the conjugacy class of a permutation $\sigma$ in $S_n$ with cycle-type having $a_i$ cycles of length $i$ is

$$
|\operatorname{Cl}(\sigma)| \;=\;\frac{|S_n|}{|C_{S_n}(\sigma)|}
\;=\;\frac{n!}{\prod_{i=1}^n\bigl(i^{\,a_i}\,a_i!\bigr)}.
$$

2. For cycle structure $(3,3,1)$ in $S_7$, we have $a_3=2$, $a_1=1$, and all other $a_i=0$.  Hence

$$
|\operatorname{Cl}(\sigma)| \;=\;\frac{7!}{3^{2}\,2!\;\times\;1^{1}\,1!}
\;=\;\frac{7!}{3^2\,2!}
\;=\;\frac{7!}{9\cdot2}
\;=\;\frac{7!}{18}.
$$

3. Keeping constants symbolic until the final simplification,

$$
\frac{7!}{18}
\;=\;\frac{5040}{18}
\;=\;280.
$$

Thus there are $280$ permutations in $S_7$ that decompose into two disjoint 3-cycles.
